            <section
              aria-label="How Kentucky occupational tax is calculated"
              class="prose"
            >
              <h2>How this Kentucky occupational tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Many Kentucky cities and counties impose an
                <strong>occupational tax</strong> (also called an
                <em>occupational license fee</em>) on wages and business net
                profits earned within their jurisdiction. This calculator
                focuses on the <strong>wage-based occupational tax</strong> that
                is typically withheld from employee paychecks.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Basic formula (percentage-based occupational tax)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm mb-1">Let:</p>
                <ul class="text-sm mb-1">
                  <li>
                    <strong>GrossPay</strong> = your pay for the period before
                    any taxes
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>PreTax</strong> = pre-tax deductions that your local
                    ordinance excludes from taxable wages
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>Rate</strong> = occupational tax rate (as a decimal,
                    e.g., 2.25% → 0.0225)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p class="text-sm mb-1">
                  Then taxable wages and occupational tax are:
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  <strong>TaxableWages</strong> = max(0, GrossPay − PreTax)<br />
                  <strong>OccupationalTax</strong> = TaxableWages × Rate
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Flat-amount occupational tax</p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  Some jurisdictions charge a
                  <strong>flat dollar amount per period</strong> instead of, or
                  in addition to, a percentage. In that case:
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  <strong>OccupationalTax</strong> = FlatAmountPerPeriod
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                This tool lets you choose either method and optionally add
                another local wage-based tax (for example, a school or transit
                tax) to see the combined impact on your net pay.
              </p>

              <h3>Pay frequency & annualization</h3>
              <p>
                To show annual estimates, the calculator multiplies your
                per-period values by a standard number of periods:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Hourly</strong>: assumes 2,080 hours per year (40
                  hours × 52 weeks)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Weekly</strong>: 52 pay periods per year</li>
                <li><strong>Biweekly</strong>: 26 pay periods per year</li>
                <li><strong>Semimonthly</strong>: 24 pay periods per year</li>
                <li><strong>Monthly</strong>: 12 pay periods per year</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Annual</strong>: 1 period per year (you enter the
                  annual amount directly)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Actual annual totals may differ if your hours, pay, or tax rates
                change during the year.
              </p>

              <h2>Important notes and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This is an <strong>educational estimator</strong>, not an
                  official filing tool.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Kentucky occupational tax rules vary by jurisdiction. Some
                  have:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Different rates for wages vs. net profits</li>
                    <li>Caps, minimums, or exemptions</li>
                    <li>
                      Special treatment for certain benefits or deductions
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  The preset rates in the dropdown are
                  <strong>examples only</strong> and may not reflect current
                  law. Always verify with the city or county’s official website,
                  forms, or ordinances.
                </li>
                <li>
                  This calculator does <strong>not</strong> compute Kentucky
                  state income tax or federal income tax. It only estimates
                  local occupational and optional other local wage-based taxes.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Tips for employees</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Check your pay stub to see the exact description and rate of
                  any occupational tax withheld.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Confirm whether your retirement contributions or health
                  premiums reduce occupational taxable wages.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you work in multiple Kentucky jurisdictions, you may owe
                  tax to more than one locality.
                </li>
                <li>
                  When in doubt, contact your employer’s payroll department or
                  the local tax administrator.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Tips for employers & payroll admins</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use this tool to sanity-check per-pay-period withholding for a
